{"title_page": "Harold S. Diehl", "text_new": "{{short description|American physician and writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       =  Harold Sheely Diehl \n| image      = \n|birth_date  = August 4, 1891\n|birth_place = [[Nittany, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date  = June 27, 1973\n|death_place = [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n| occupation = Physician, writer}}\n\n'''Harold Sheely Diehl''' (August 4, 1891 - June 27, 1973) was an American [[physician]], [[public health]] educator and writer. \n\n==Biography==\n\nDiehl graduated in 1912 from [[Gettysburg College]] and obtained his medical degree from the [[University of Minnesota]] in 1916.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1973/06/28/archives/dr-harold-diehl-of-cancer-society-researcher-who-warned-of-perils.html Dr. Harold Diehl of Cancer Society]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 23 April 2020.</ref> He was director of the Student Health Service at the University of Minnesota.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>  He became Professor of Preventive Medicine and Public Health and was appointed dean of Medical Sciences.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> In 1957, he joined the Cancer Society as senior vice president of research and medical affairs.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> He retired in 1968, but remained a consultant for the Cancer Society.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\nIn 1938, Diehl and colleagues published results from a trial on the efficacy of vaccines for the [[common cold]]. The study has been cited as one of the first instances of a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial.<ref name=\"BMJ\">{{cite journal|author=Waller, L. A.|year=1997|title=A note on Harold S. Diehl, randomization, and clinical trials|journal=[[Controlled Clinical Trials]]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9129861|volume=18|issue=2|pages=180-183}}</ref> \n\nDiehl's ''Textbook of Healthful Living'' first published in 1935 went through many editions. The comprehensive text of personal and public hygiene was positively reviewed in medical journals.<ref>{{cite journal|author=MacLean, D. L.|year=1936|title=Reviewed Work: Healthful Living by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[Canadian Public Health Journal]]|volume=27|issue=2|pages=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Schneider, B. Aubrey|year=1946|title=Reviewed Work: Textbook of Healthful Living. by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]|volume=21|issue=1|pages=106}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith 1950\">{{cite journal|author=J. W. H. Smith|year=1950|title=Reviewed Work: Textbook of Healthful Living by Harold S. Diehl|journal=Bios|volume=21|issue=3|pages=208}}</ref>\n\nThe Harold S. Diehl Award was established in 1962 to honour Diehl.<ref>[https://med.umn.edu/about/honors-awards/alumni-awards/harold-s-diehl-award \"Harold S. Diehl Award\"]. [[University of Minnesota]]. Retrieved 23 April 2020.</ref> He died aged 81 from heart disease at [[United Hospital]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\n==''Tobacco and Your Health''==\n\nDiehl wrote about the health risks of [[smoking]] from the 1930s.<ref>Rybak, Deborah Caulfield; Phelps, David. (1998). ''Smoked: The Inside Story of the Minnesota Tobacco Trial''. MSP Books. p. 310. ISBN 978-0964190849</ref> He was a leading proponent of the relationship between smoking and [[lung cancer]].<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> \n\nHe authored ''Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy'' in 1969. A review of the book noted that Diehl \"presents a straightforward account of the scientific and medical evidence identifying tobacco as a causative agent in lung cancer, cardiovascular disease, chronic bronchitis and emphysema, and other diseases.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Friedman, Suzanne H.|year=1969|title=Reviewed Work: Tobacco and Your Health; The Smoking Controversy by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[The American Journal of Nursing]]|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3454098|volume=69|issue=9|pages=1988\u20131990}}</ref> In 1969, physician [[Luther Terry]] positively reviewed the book in the ''[[American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health]]'' noting that \"it presents the most comprehensive review available to date detailing the health consequences of this habit.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Terry, Luther L.|year=1969|title=Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy|journal=[[American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health]]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1226778/?page=1|volume=59|issue=11|pages=2111}}</ref>\n\nPhysician [[Walter C. Alvarez]] commented that \"Diehl is a great humanitarian, a great teacher, a great gatherer of facts, and a fine writer of delightful prose. I don't see how anyone can question his mass of statistics.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Alvarez, Walter C.|year=1970|title=Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy.|journal=Arch Intern Med|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamainternalmedicine/article-abstract/577010|volume=126|issue=1|pages=178}}</ref> In 1970, the book was positively reviewed in the ''[[The BMJ|British Medical Journal]]'' which concluded that \"cause and effect are established beyond reasonable doubt by the overwhelming weight of evidence linking cigarette smoking with serious disease... [t]his book should effectively reinforce the movement which must one day turn public opinion against the cigarette, or stimulate the development of a safe one.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Birdwood, George|year=1970|title=Reviewed Work: Tobacco And Your Health: The Smoking Controversy by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[The BMJ|The British Medical Journal]]|volume=1|issue=5687|pages=40}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism of fad diets==\n\nDiehl criticized [[Fad diets|dietary fads]] such as the [[alkaline diet]], [[food combining]], [[raw foodism]], strict [[vegetarianism]] and [[water fasting]].<ref name=\"Diehl 1950\">Diehl, Harold Sheely. (1950). [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.11782/page/n119/mode/2up ''Elements of Healthful Living'']. McGraw-Hill Book Company. pp. 110-112</ref> Diehl suggested that most vegetarians are not really vegetarian because they consume dairy or egg products. He commented that the human digestive tract is not intended for an exclusive herbivorous diet.<ref name=\"Diehl 1950\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n*''Textbook of Healthful Living'' (1935, 1950)<ref name=\"Smith 1950\"/>\n*[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.11782/page/n3/mode/2up ''Elements of Healthful Living''] (1950)\n*''Personal Health and Community Hygiene'' (with [[Ruth Boynton|Ruth E. Boynton]], 1951)\n*''The Health of College Students'' (with Charles E. Shepard, 1939)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Smiley, D. F.|year=1940|title=Reviewed Work: The Health of College Students by Harold S. Diehl, Charles E. Shepard|journal=[[The American Journal of Psychology]]|volume=53|issue=3|pages=481-482}}</ref>\n*''Health and Safety for You'' (with Anita D. Laton, 1954)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schneider, B. Aubrey|year=1955|title=Reviewed Work: Health and Safety for You by Harold S. Diehl, Anita D. Laton|journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]|volume=30|issue=3|pages=283}}</ref>\n*''Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy'' (1969)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:American health educators]]\n[[Category:American health and wellness writers]]\n[[Category:Anti-smoking activists]]\n[[Category:Critics of vegetarianism]]\n[[Category:Diet food advocates]]\n[[Category:Gettysburg College alumni]]\n[[Category:Hygienists]]\n[[Category:American public health doctors]]\n[[Category:Tobacco researchers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American physician and writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       =  Harold Sheely Diehl \n| image      = \n|birth_date  = August 4, 1891\n|birth_place = [[Nittany, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date  = June 27, 1973\n|death_place = [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n| occupation = Physician, writer}}\n\n'''Harold Sheely Diehl''' (August 4, 1891 - June 27, 1973) was an American [[physician]], [[public health]] educator and writer. \n\n==Biography==\n\nDiehl graduated in 1912 from [[Gettysburg College]] and obtained his medical degree from the [[University of Minnesota]] in 1916.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1973/06/28/archives/dr-harold-diehl-of-cancer-society-researcher-who-warned-of-perils.html Dr. Harold Diehl of Cancer Society]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 23 April 2020.</ref> He was director of the Student Health Service at the University of Minnesota.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>  He became Professor of Preventive Medicine and Public Health and was appointed dean of Medical Sciences.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> In 1957, he joined the Cancer Society as senior vice president of research and medical affairs.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> He retired in 1968, but remained a consultant for the Cancer Society.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\nIn 1938, Diehl and colleagues published results from a trial on the efficacy of vaccines for the [[common cold]]. The study has been cited as one of the first instances of a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial.<ref name=\"BMJ\">{{cite journal|author=Waller, L. A.|year=1997|title=A note on Harold S. Diehl, randomization, and clinical trials|journal=[[Controlled Clinical Trials]]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9129861|volume=18|issue=2|pages=180-183}}</ref> \n\nDiehl's ''Textbook of Healthful Living'' first published in 1935 went through many editions. The comprehensive text of personal and public hygiene was positively reviewed in medical journals.<ref>{{cite journal|author=MacLean, D. L.|year=1936|title=Reviewed Work: Healthful Living by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[Canadian Public Health Journal]]|volume=27|issue=2|pages=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Schneider, B. Aubrey|year=1946|title=Reviewed Work: Textbook of Healthful Living. by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]|volume=21|issue=1|pages=106}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith 1950\">{{cite journal|author=J. W. H. Smith|year=1950|title=Reviewed Work: Textbook of Healthful Living by Harold S. Diehl|journal=Bios|volume=21|issue=3|pages=208}}</ref>\n\nThe Harold S. Diehl Award was established in 1962 to honour Diehl.<ref>[https://med.umn.edu/about/honors-awards/alumni-awards/harold-s-diehl-award \"Harold S. Diehl Award\"]. [[University of Minnesota]]. Retrieved 23 April 2020.</ref> He died age 81 from heart disease at [[United Hospital]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\n==''Tobacco and Your Health''==\n\nDiehl wrote about the health risks of [[smoking]] from the 1930s.<ref>Rybak, Deborah Caulfield; Phelps, David. (1998). ''Smoked: The Inside Story of the Minnesota Tobacco Trial''. MSP Books. p. 310. ISBN 978-0964190849</ref> He was a leading proponent of the relationship between smoking and [[lung cancer]].<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> \n\nHe authored ''Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy'' in 1969. A review of the book noted that Diehl \"presents a straightforward account of the scientific and medical evidence identifying tobacco as a causative agent in lung cancer, cardiovascular disease, chronic bronchitis and emphysema, and other diseases.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Friedman, Suzanne H.|year=1969|title=Reviewed Work: Tobacco and Your Health; The Smoking Controversy by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[The American Journal of Nursing]]|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3454098|volume=69|issue=9|pages=1988\u20131990}}</ref> In 1969, physician [[Luther Terry]] positively reviewed the book in the ''[[American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health]]'' noting that \"it presents the most comprehensive review available to date detailing the health consequences of this habit.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Terry, Luther L.|year=1969|title=Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy|journal=[[American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health]]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1226778/?page=1|volume=59|issue=11|pages=2111}}</ref>\n\nPhysician [[Walter C. Alvarez]] commented that \"Diehl is a great humanitarian, a great teacher, a great gatherer of facts, and a fine writer of delightful prose. I don't see how anyone can question his mass of statistics.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Alvarez, Walter C.|year=1970|title=Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy.|journal=Arch Intern Med|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamainternalmedicine/article-abstract/577010|volume=126|issue=1|pages=178}}</ref> In 1970, the book was positively reviewed in the ''[[The BMJ|British Medical Journal]]'' which concluded that \"cause and effect are established beyond reasonable doubt by the overwhelming weight of evidence linking cigarette smoking with serious disease... [t]his book should effectively reinforce the movement which must one day turn public opinion against the cigarette, or stimulate the development of a safe one.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Birdwood, George|year=1970|title=Reviewed Work: Tobacco And Your Health: The Smoking Controversy by Harold S. Diehl|journal=[[The BMJ|The British Medical Journal]]|volume=1|issue=5687|pages=40}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism of fad diets==\n\nDiehl criticized [[Fad diets|dietary fads]] such as the [[alkaline diet]], [[food combining]], [[raw foodism]], strict [[vegetarianism]] and [[water fasting]].<ref name=\"Diehl 1950\">Diehl, Harold Sheely. (1950). [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.11782/page/n119/mode/2up ''Elements of Healthful Living'']. McGraw-Hill Book Company. pp. 110-112</ref> Diehl suggested that most vegetarians are not really vegetarian because they consume dairy or egg products. He commented that the human digestive tract is not intended for an exclusive herbivorous diet.<ref name=\"Diehl 1950\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n*''Textbook of Healthful Living'' (1935, 1950)<ref name=\"Smith 1950\"/>\n*[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.11782/page/n3/mode/2up ''Elements of Healthful Living''] (1950)\n*''Personal Health and Community Hygiene'' (with [[Ruth Boynton|Ruth E. Boynton]], 1951)\n*''The Health of College Students'' (with Charles E. Shepard, 1939)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Smiley, D. F.|year=1940|title=Reviewed Work: The Health of College Students by Harold S. Diehl, Charles E. Shepard|journal=[[The American Journal of Psychology]]|volume=53|issue=3|pages=481-482}}</ref>\n*''Health and Safety for You'' (with Anita D. Laton, 1954)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schneider, B. Aubrey|year=1955|title=Reviewed Work: Health and Safety for You by Harold S. Diehl, Anita D. Laton|journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]|volume=30|issue=3|pages=283}}</ref>\n*''Tobacco and Your Health: The Smoking Controversy'' (1969)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:American health educators]]\n[[Category:American health and wellness writers]]\n[[Category:Anti-smoking activists]]\n[[Category:Critics of vegetarianism]]\n[[Category:Diet food advocates]]\n[[Category:Gettysburg College alumni]]\n[[Category:Hygienists]]\n[[Category:American public health doctors]]\n[[Category:Tobacco researchers]]\n", "name_user": "Psychologist Guy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_S._Diehl"}
{"title_page": "Rich Lesser", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Richard \"Rich\" Lesser\n| image              = Photo of Rich Lesser - World Economic Forum.JPG\n| caption            = Rich Lesser at the 2012 [[World Economic Forum]] in Davos\n| birth_date         = 1962\n| occupation         = [[Management Consultant]], [[Strategist]]\n| citizenship        = [[Americans|American]]\n| title              = [[CEO]]\n| employer           = [[Boston Consulting Group]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Michigan]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Harvard Business School]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n}}\n\n'''Richard \"Rich\" Lesser''' (born 1962) is an American businessman currently serving as the [[CEO]] of American global management consultancy the [[Boston Consulting Group]] (BCG). He attended the [[University of Michigan]], where he graduated with highest honors ([[Summa Cum Laude|S''umma Cum Laude'']]) with a bachelor's degree in Chemical Engineering, and then [[Harvard Business School]] as a [[Baker Scholar]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://alumni.umich.edu/alumnus/notable-alumni/|title=Notable Alumni|work=Alumni Association of the University of Michigan|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLesser started his career as a process development engineer and group leader at [[Procter & Gamble]] after graduating from the [[University of Michigan, Ann Arbor]] in 1983. Following this, he attended [[Harvard Business School]], where he was named a [[Baker scholar|Baker Scholar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=12485525&privcapId=135794 |title=Executive Profile: Richard I. Lesser |work=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=2013-03-17 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Lesser joined [[Boston Consulting Group|BCG]] as a consultant, and his client work focused on strategy, operations, leaderships, and large-scale transformation in the health care and consumer sectors. He was elected to partner in less than 10 years and served as the head of the firm's New York Metro offices from 2000 to 2009. In this period, the New York office became the firm's largest in the country, based on revenue and headcount. He was elected to the firm's Executive Committee in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/09/idUSnMKW72114a+1c0+MKW20130109|title=BCG Press Release |publisher=Thomson Reuters |date=2013-01-09 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nHe has been active in efforts to redirect corporate and business unit strategy, streamline organizations, improve productivity, and ensure successful post-merger integration. He played a pivotal role in helping BCG become the only global management consulting firm to grow strongly through the 2008 recession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultingmag.com/article/ART631951|title=Top 25 Consultants, 2009: Rich Lesser |work=Consulting Magazine |date=2009-06-01 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lesser was named BCG's Chairman for North and South America. In the same year, ''Consulting Magazine'' named him one of the industry's Top 25 most influential consultants for excellence in Healthcare. He has spoken at the [[World Economic Forum]] and [[The New York Forum]], and  wrote articles in the ''[[Harvard Business Review]]'' and Fortune ''[https://fortune.com/author/rich-lesser/]''. Lesser was BCG\u2019s chairman for North and South America from 2009 to 2012.\n\nIn May 2012, he was named the successor of [[Hans-Paul B\u00fcrkner]] as the Global Chief Executive Officer of [[The Boston Consulting Group]] when B\u00fcrkner stepped down in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcg.com/media/pressreleasedetails.aspx?id=tcm:12-105846|title=The Boston Consulting Group Names Rich Lesser New President and CEO |publisher=The Boston Consulting Group |date=2012-05-20 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref> \n\nUnder his leadership, BCG has continued its strong global growth across all regions and practices, fueled by investments in new offices, digital and analytics, and capabilities to drive innovation and transformation. Rich oversaw the launch of BCG Digital Venture ''[https://www.bcgdv.com/]'', a builder and accelerator of digital businesses; BCG Gamma ''[https://www.bcg.com/beyond-consulting/bcg-gamma/default.aspx]'', a cutting-edge advanced analytics, machine-learning and AI team; BCG TURN ''[https://www.bcg.com/en-es/capabilities/transformation/turnaround-restructuring.aspx]'', a rapid performance acceleration unit; and more recently, the Center for Climate Action.\n\nRich Lesser is a member of several leading organizations, such as the [[World Economic Forum]]\u2019s International Business Council, the WEF's Alliance of CEO Climate Leaders,<ref>{{cite web |title=Alliance of CEO Climate Leaders |url=https://www.weforum.org/projects/alliance-of-ceo-climate-leaders |website=World Economic forum |publisher=World Economic Forum}}</ref> the US [[Business Roundtable]], and Helena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centreforpublicimpact.org/author/rich-lesser/|title=Rich Lesser, Author at Centre for Public Impact (CPI)|website=Centre for Public Impact (CPI)|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/authors/rich-lesser/|title=Authors|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessroundtable.org/about/members/rich-lesser|title=Rich Lesser {{!}} Business Roundtable|website=www.businessroundtable.org|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref> He has also accelerated BCG\u2019s strong investments in social impact through its many partnerships, including the [[World Food Programme]], [[Save the Children]], [[Teach For All|Teach for All]], and the [[World Wildlife Fund]], along with many global health and environment initiatives.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wfp.org/stories/partner-profile-boston-consulting-group|title=UN World Food Programme|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.savethechildren.net/about%20us/our-corporate-partners/our-partnership-boston-consulting-group-bcg|title=Our partnership with the Boston Consulting Group (BCG) {{!}} Save the Children International|work=Save the Children International|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcg.com/en-us/industries/social-impact/teach-for-all.aspx|title=Teach For All \u2013 BCG\u2019s Global Social Impact Partner|language=en|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wwf.panda.org/get_involved/partner_with_wwf/business_partnerships/bcg/|title=The Boston Consulting Group|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Lesser joined a business forum assembled by then [[President-elect of the United States|president-elect]] [[Donald J. Trump|Donald Trump]] to provide strategic and policy advice on economic issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bryan|first1=Bob|title=Trump is forming an economic advisory team with the CEOs of Disney, General Motors, JPMorgan, and more|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-strategic-and-policy-forum-includes-dimon-iger-schwarzman-2016-12|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=Business Insider|date=2 Dec 2016}}</ref> In October 2018, Lesser began his third three-year term as CEO of Boston Consulting Group. \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Hans-Paul B\u00fcrkner]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[CEO]] <br>[[Boston Consulting Group]]|\n| years = 2013\u2013Present\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = \u2014\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Steve Gunby\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Chairman]], North and South America <br>[[Boston Consulting Group]]|\n| years = 2009\u20132012\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Pascal Cotte\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==Related pages==\n* [[Boston Consulting Group|The Boston Consulting Group]]\n* [[Hans-Paul B\u00fcrkner]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bcg.com/about_bcg/leadership/executive_committee.aspx#tcm127161 BCG Leadership Biography]\n* [http://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?id=223834892 LinkedIn: Rich Lesser]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=PT57nFnQ4WYC&oi=fnd&pg=PP1&dq=%22richard+lesser%22+boston+consulting+group&ots=j6-0QhfK6C&sig=AxZd3-NlDkg0r880O45fOgSa80c Own The Future: 50 Ways to Win (co-authored by Lesser)]\n* [https://www.bcgperspectives.com/commentaries/author/126099?pageNumber=1 BCG Perspectives Profile]\n* [http://live.wsj.com/video/bcg-boss-what-it-takes/C184BB1B-3DCA-4284-9A76-A5BA9AE3C904.html#!C184BB1B-3DCA-4284-9A76-A5BA9AE3C904 Wall Street Journal: What It Takes (Interview)]\n* [http://www.weforum.org/contributors/rich-lesser World Economic Forum Profile]\n* [http://www.bcg.com/documents/file133479.pdf Wall Street Journal Interview: Wrangling Big Issues to Draw Clients]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lesser, Rich}}\n[[Category:American management consultants]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Boston Consulting Group people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Richard \"Rich\" Lesser\n| image              = Photo of Rich Lesser - World Economic Forum.JPG\n| caption            = Rich Lesser at the 2012 [[World Economic Forum]] in Davos\n| birth_date         = 1962\n| occupation         = [[Management Consultant]], [[Strategist]]\n| citizenship        = [[Americans|American]]\n| title              = [[CEO]]\n| employer           = [[Boston Consulting Group]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Michigan]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Harvard Business School]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n}}\n\n'''Richard \"Rich\" Lesser''' (born 1962) is an American businessman currently serving as the [[CEO]] of American global management consultancy the [[Boston Consulting Group]] (BCG). He attended the [[University of Michigan]], where he graduated with highest honors ([[Summa Cum Laude|S''umma Cum Laude'']]) with a bachelor's degree in Chemical Engineering, and then [[Harvard Business School]] as a [[Baker Scholar]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://alumni.umich.edu/alumnus/notable-alumni/|title=Notable Alumni|work=Alumni Association of the University of Michigan|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLesser started his career as a process development engineer and group leader at [[Procter & Gamble]] after graduating from the [[University of Michigan, Ann Arbor]] in 1983. Following this, he attended [[Harvard Business School]], where he was named a [[Baker scholar|Baker Scholar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=12485525&privcapId=135794 |title=Executive Profile: Richard I. Lesser |work=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=2013-03-17 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Lesser joined [[Boston Consulting Group|BCG]] as a consultant, and his client work focused on strategy, operations, leaderships, and large-scale transformation in the health care and consumer sectors. He was elected to partner in less than 10 years and served as the head of the firm's New York Metro offices from 2000 to 2009. In this period, the New York office became the firm's largest in the country, based on revenue and headcount. He was elected to the firm's Executive Committee in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/09/idUSnMKW72114a+1c0+MKW20130109|title=BCG Press Release |publisher=Thomson Reuters |date=2013-01-09 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nHe has been active in efforts to redirect corporate and business unit strategy, streamline organizations, improve productivity, and ensure successful post-merger integration. He played a pivotal role in helping BCG become the only global management consulting firm to grow strongly through the 2008 recession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultingmag.com/article/ART631951|title=Top 25 Consultants, 2009: Rich Lesser |work=Consulting Magazine |date=2009-06-01 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lesser was named BCG's Chairman for North and South America. In the same year, ''Consulting Magazine'' named him one of the industry's Top 25 most influential consultants for excellence in Healthcare. He has spoken at the [[World Economic Forum]] and [[The New York Forum]], and  wrote articles in the ''[[Harvard Business Review]]'' and Fortune ''[https://fortune.com/author/rich-lesser/]''. Lesser was BCG\u2019s chairman for North and South America from 2009 to 2012.\n\nIn May 2012, he was named the successor of [[Hans-Paul B\u00fcrkner]] as the Global Chief Executive Officer of [[The Boston Consulting Group]] when B\u00fcrkner stepped down in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcg.com/media/pressreleasedetails.aspx?id=tcm:12-105846|title=The Boston Consulting Group Names Rich Lesser New President and CEO |publisher=The Boston Consulting Group |date=2012-05-20 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref> \n\nUnder his leadership, BCG has continued its strong global growth across all regions and practices, fueled by investments in new offices, digital and analytics, and capabilities to drive innovation and transformation. Rich oversaw the launch of BCG Digital Venture ''[https://www.bcgdv.com/]'', a builder and accelerator of digital businesses; BCG Gamma ''[https://www.bcg.com/beyond-consulting/bcg-gamma/default.aspx]'', a cutting-edge advanced analytics, machine-learning and AI team; BCG TURN ''[https://www.bcg.com/en-es/capabilities/transformation/turnaround-restructuring.aspx]'', a rapid performance acceleration unit; and more recently, the Center for Climate Action.\n\nRich Lesser is a member of several leading organizations, such as the [[World Economic Forum]]\u2019s International Business Council, the WEF's Alliance of CEO Climate Leaders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alliance of CEO Climate Leaders |url=https://www.weforum.org/projects/alliance-of-ceo-climate-leaders |website=World Economic forum |publisher=World Economic Forum}}</ref>, the US [[Business Roundtable]], and Helena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centreforpublicimpact.org/author/rich-lesser/|title=Rich Lesser, Author at Centre for Public Impact (CPI)|website=Centre for Public Impact (CPI)|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/authors/rich-lesser/|title=Authors|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessroundtable.org/about/members/rich-lesser|title=Rich Lesser {{!}} Business Roundtable|website=www.businessroundtable.org|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref> He has also accelerated BCG\u2019s strong investments in social impact through its many partnerships, including the [[World Food Programme]], [[Save the Children]], [[Teach For All|Teach for All]], and the [[World Wildlife Fund]], along with many global health and environment initiatives.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wfp.org/stories/partner-profile-boston-consulting-group|title=UN World Food Programme|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.savethechildren.net/about%20us/our-corporate-partners/our-partnership-boston-consulting-group-bcg|title=Our partnership with the Boston Consulting Group (BCG) {{!}} Save the Children International|work=Save the Children International|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcg.com/en-us/industries/social-impact/teach-for-all.aspx|title=Teach For All \u2013 BCG\u2019s Global Social Impact Partner|language=en|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wwf.panda.org/get_involved/partner_with_wwf/business_partnerships/bcg/|title=The Boston Consulting Group|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Lesser joined a business forum assembled by then [[President-elect of the United States|president-elect]] [[Donald J. Trump|Donald Trump]] to provide strategic and policy advice on economic issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bryan|first1=Bob|title=Trump is forming an economic advisory team with the CEOs of Disney, General Motors, JPMorgan, and more|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-strategic-and-policy-forum-includes-dimon-iger-schwarzman-2016-12|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=Business Insider|date=2 Dec 2016}}</ref> In October 2018, Lesser began his third three-year term as CEO of Boston Consulting Group. \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Hans-Paul B\u00fcrkner]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[CEO]] <br>[[Boston Consulting Group]]|\n| years = 2013\u2013Present\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = \u2014\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Steve Gunby\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Chairman]], North and South America <br>[[Boston Consulting Group]]|\n| years = 2009\u20132012\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Pascal Cotte\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==Related pages==\n* [[Boston Consulting Group|The Boston Consulting Group]]\n* [[Hans-Paul B\u00fcrkner]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bcg.com/about_bcg/leadership/executive_committee.aspx#tcm127161 BCG Leadership Biography]\n* [http://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?id=223834892 LinkedIn: Rich Lesser]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=PT57nFnQ4WYC&oi=fnd&pg=PP1&dq=%22richard+lesser%22+boston+consulting+group&ots=j6-0QhfK6C&sig=AxZd3-NlDkg0r880O45fOgSa80c Own The Future: 50 Ways to Win (co-authored by Lesser)]\n* [https://www.bcgperspectives.com/commentaries/author/126099?pageNumber=1 BCG Perspectives Profile]\n* [http://live.wsj.com/video/bcg-boss-what-it-takes/C184BB1B-3DCA-4284-9A76-A5BA9AE3C904.html#!C184BB1B-3DCA-4284-9A76-A5BA9AE3C904 Wall Street Journal: What It Takes (Interview)]\n* [http://www.weforum.org/contributors/rich-lesser World Economic Forum Profile]\n* [http://www.bcg.com/documents/file133479.pdf Wall Street Journal Interview: Wrangli