tp://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-05-22/comcast-the-mets-and-other-winners-in-the-new-man-city-yankees-mls-franchise |title=Comcast, the Mets, and Other Winners in the New Man City-Yankees MLS Franchise |last=Stock |first=Kyle |access-date=July 28, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| chrtitle = CEO\n| chairman = Xu-Ying Yang\n| mgrtitle = Head coach\n| manager = [[Oliver Schneider]]\n| league = [[Major League Baseball]]\n| current = 2020 New York City FC season\n| season = [[2019 Major League Soccer season|2019]]\n| position = [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]]: 1st<br /> Overall: 2nd<br /> [[2019 MLS Cup Playoffs|Playoffs]]: Conference Semifinals\n| website = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z3Uo9Vj6yk0\n| American = true\n| pattern_b1 = _nycfc_home_2019\n| pattern_la1 = _nycfc_home_2019\n| pattern_ra1 = _nycfc_home_2019\n| pattern_sh1 = _nycfc_home_2019\n| pattern_so1 = _nycfc_home_2019\n| pattern_la2 = _nycfc20a\n| pattern_b2 = _nycfc20A\n| pattern_ra2 = _nycfc20a\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = _nycfc20a\n| shorts2 = 001F48\n| socks2 = 001F48\n}}\n\n'''New York City Baseball Club''' is worse than the redbulls an [[Association football|soccer]] club based in [[New York City]] that competes in [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), the highest level of [[United States soccer league system|American soccer]], as a member of the league's [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]].\n\nNew York City played its first game in [[2015 MLS season|2015]], as the twentieth overall expansion team of the league;<ref name=\"OSstatement\">{{Cite press release |title=Club Statement 21 May |date=May 21, 2013 |publisher=Manchester City FC |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Club-news/2013/May/Club-announcement-New-York-City-FC-to-launch-21-May |access-date=May 21, 2013}}</ref> it is the first franchise to be based in the city, and the second in the [[New York metropolitan area]], after the [[New York Red Bulls]], with whom they contest the [[Hudson River Derby]].<ref name=\"mlb.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130521&content_id=48162622&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Yanks, Manchester City awarded MLS expansion team |date=May 21, 2013 |publisher=Major League Baseball}}</ref> Since 2015, the club have played at [[Yankee Stadium]] in [[The Bronx]].\n\n[[Jason Kreis]] was appointed as the club's first coach, remaining for a single year prior to being replaced by [[Patrick Vieira]]. Vieira guided New York City to their first [[MLS Cup]] [[MLS Cup Playoffs|playoff]] appearance the following season, as well as a runner-up berth in the [[Supporters' Shield]] in [[2017 Major League Soccer season#Conference standings|2017]]. Vieira's teams also set [[Major League Soccer records and statistics|Major League Soccer records]] for the largest improvement in wins for a consecutive season.\n\nBased on attendance from the [[2019 Major League Soccer season|2019 regular season]], New York City's attendance was ninth-largest in the league.<ref name=\"2019 MLS Attendance\">{{Cite web |url=https://soccerstadiumdigest.com/2019-mls-attendance/ |title=2019 MLS Attendance |publisher=Soccer Stadium Digest |access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated the franchise was the seventh most valuable in MLS, worth over $385&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"Forbes Football Valuations\">{{Cite magazine |title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams 2019 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2019/11/04/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2019-atlanta-stays-on-top-as-expansion-fees-sale-prices-surge/#3e7ff7f51b58/ |magazine=Forbes |access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Foundation===\nMLS had an interest in placing a second team in the New York area as early as 2006, when the MetroStars' exclusive territorial rights reverted to the league as a condition of the club's sale to [[Red Bull GmbH]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/10/sports/soccer/red-bull-is-new-owner-and-name-of-metrostars.html |title=Red Bull Is New Owner, and Name, of MetroStars |last=Bell |first=Jack |date=March 10, 2006 |work=The New York Times |access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref> By the following year, the league had held talks with several groups, including [[New York Mets]] owner [[Fred Wilpon]] and his family, about owning the second New York franchise.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/17/sports/soccer/17mls.html |title=Mets Said to Be Looking into an M.L.S. Franchise |last=Bell |first=Jack |date=June 17, 2007 |work=The New York Times |access-date=February 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MLSeyes\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/mls-commissioner-eyes-possible-new-york-franchise-2013 |title=MLS commissioner eyes possible New York franchise for 2013 |date=May 7, 2010 |work=mlssoccer.com |access-date=May 21, 2013}}</ref> The Wilpons' interest in MLS reportedly faded following the family's losses in the [[Madoff investment scandal]], but the league continued to look for investors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2009/07/18/wilpons-cant-afford-mls-team/ |title=Wilpons can't afford MLS team |last=Lewis |first=Brian |date=July 18, 2009 |work=New York Post |access-date=February 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/02/sports/soccer/02cosmos.html |title=Cosmos Begin Anew, With Eye Toward M.L.S. |last=Bell |first=Jack |date=August 1, 2010 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, MLS commissioner [[Don Garber]] officially announced the league's intent to make its 20th franchise a second team in the New York area. At that point, the league hoped to have the new team beginning operations by 2013.<ref name=\"MLSeyes\" /> Garber also held discussions with the owners of the rebooted [[New York Cosmos (2010)|New York Cosmos]], but they balked at the league's expansion fee and single-entity structure and decided not to apply for entry, instead joining the second-tier [[North American Soccer League]].<ref name=\"joinnasl2013\">{{Cite web |url=http://nycosmos.com/news/new-york-cosmos-join-nasl-2013 |title=New York Cosmos Returns to NASL |last=O'Brien |first=Seamus |date=July 12, 2012 |website=nycosmos.com |publisher=New York Cosmos |location=New York City |access-date=May 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/mls-focused-making-ny-club-its-20th-team |title=MLS focused on making NY club its 20th team |date=November 16, 2010 |work=mlssoccer.com |access-date=May 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite podcast |url=http://example.org |title=The Soccer File |host=Simon Evans |date=December 6, 2016 |time=18:44 |access-date=February 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGarber had previously cultivated an interest in acquiring investment from a major European soccer club to be owners of a future franchise, and in December 2008, he announced a bid for a [[Expansion of Major League Soccer#Miami (2008\u201309)|Miami expansion team]] led by [[FC Barcelona]]. The team was to begin play in 2010 if accepted, however, the bid eventually fell through.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/1110/major-league-soccer/2009/02/11/1105039/garber-barcamiami-team-would-start-in-2010 |title=Garber: Barca/Miami Team Would Start in 2010 |last=Lalas |first=Greg |date=February 11, 2009 |work=Goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/1110/major-league-soccer/2009/03/03/1137156/miami-barcelona-mls-campaign-is-dead |title=Miami Barcelona MLS Campaign Is Dead |date=March 3, 2009 |work=Goal.com}}</ref> Garber also briefly discussed Barcelona investing in a New York franchise, before moving the focus to [[Miami]].<ref name=\"Bennett\" />\n\nIn 2012, [[Ferran Soriano]], Barcelona's vice president at the time of the Miami bid, was appointed [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] CEO, prompting Garber to reach out to him about a New York City team.<ref name=\"Bennett\">{{Cite news |url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/relegationzone/id/866?cc=5901 |title=Ambitious Garber ready for next challenge |last=Bennett |first=Roger |date=May 28, 2013 |work=Relegation Zone |publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref> In December 2012, unnamed sources told the media that Manchester City were close to being announced as the new owners of the 20th team of MLS, and the brand name \"New York City Football Club\" was trademarked, although the club quickly denied the report.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-12-14/manchester-city-said-close-to-becoming-owner-of-mls-queens-team.html |title=Manchester City Said Close to Being Awarded MLS Queens Team |last=Soshnick |first=Scott |date=December 15, 2012 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=May 21, 2013}}</ref> However, Garber announced in March 2013 that he was almost ready to unveil the new expansion team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/03/17/mls-commissioner-don-garber-talks-nyc2-progress-florida-expansion-champions- |title=MLS Commissioner Don Garber talks NYC2 progress, Florida expansion, Champions League schedule tweak |date=March 17, 2013 |work=mlssoccer.com |access-date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nManchester City, in association with the [[New York Yankees]] baseball team, paid the $100&nbsp;million expansion fee to join the league.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mikeozanian/2013/07/05/the-economics-behind-new-yorks-100-million-mls-team/ |title=The Economics Behind New York's $100 Million MLS Team |last=Ozanian |first=Mike |date=July 5, 2013 |work=Forbes |access-date=February 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/22/sports/soccer/manchester-city-and-yankees-to-own-mls-franchise-in-new-york.html|title=A Team Is Born, but Not All Cheer |last=Belson |first=Ken |date=May 21, 2013 |work=The New York Times |access-date=May 21, 2013 |last2=Charles V. Bagli}}</ref> New York City Football Club, LLC was also registered with the New York State Department on May 7, 2013,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://appext20.dos.ny.gov/corp_public/CORPSEARCH.ENTITY_INFORMATION?p_nameid=4396707&p_corpid=4399753&p_entity_name=new%20york%20city%20football%20club&p_name_type=A&p_search_type=BEGINS&p_srch_results_page=0 |title=Entity Information |work=NYS Division of Corporations, State Records and UCC |access-date=May 25, 2013}}</ref> and on May 21, the team was officially announced as the 20th Major League Soccer franchise.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/05/21/major-league-soccer-announces-new-york-expansion-team-new-york-city-football |title=Major League Soccer announces New York expansion team: New York City Football Club |date=May 21, 2013 |work=mlssoccer.com |access-date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2013, the club named former [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] and Manchester City midfielder [[Claudio Reyna]] as its {{Not a typo|director of football operations}}, responsible for coaching staff and player recruitment ahead of the team's inaugural MLS season in 2015.<ref name=\"MLS-reyna\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/05/22/new-york-city-fc-name-claudio-reyna-director-football-operations |title=New York City FC name Claudio Reyna director of football operations |date=May 22, 2013 |work=mlssoccer.com |access-date=May 22, 2013}}</ref> Reyna, a [[New Jersey]] native, also played for the nearby [[New York Red Bulls]]. He said he had begun identifying candidates to be the club's head coach, but would not name one in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/05/22/new-york-city-fcs-claudio-reyna-says-head-coach-wont-be-named-2013 |title=New York City FC's Claudio Reyna says head coach won't be named in 2013 |last=Borg |first=Simon |date=May 22, 2013 |work=mlssoccer.com}}</ref> The team announced an English-language radio deal with [[WFAN (AM)|WFAN]] on October 3, 2013.<ref name=\"WFAN\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2013/October/NewBroadcastDealWithWFAN |title=Broadcast Deal with WFAN |date=October 3, 2013 |work=nycfc.com |access-date=October 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe club made their first recruitment dealing in off-field matters on September 6, 2013, when they hired former [[Rutgers University]] Athletic Director [[Tim Pernetti]] to serve as Chief Business Officer, part of a five-year deal with the university.<ref name=\"Pernetti\">{{Cite news |url=http://nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2013/September/New%20York%20City%20Chief%20Business%20Officer%20appointed |title=Tim Pernetti appointed as CBO |date=September 9, 2013 |work=nycfc.com}}</ref> Further hirings were made in mid-November, when three experienced administrators were appointed to Vice President roles.<ref name=\"3VPs\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2013/November/New-York-City-Football-Club-Unveils-Front-Office-Hires? |title=New York City Football Club Unveils Front Office Hires |date=November 12, 2013 |work=nycfc.com |access-date=November 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 11, 2013, [[Jason Kreis]] was announced as the first head coach of the new franchise, having reached the end of his contract at [[Real Salt Lake]] and declined an extension.<ref name=\"Kreis\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2013/December/Head-Coach? |title=Jason Kreis named as Head Coach |date=December 11, 2013 |work=nycfc.com |access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> The move came just four days after he missed out on lifting his second [[MLS Cup]] with the [[Utah]] team, losing on penalties to [[Sporting Kansas City]]. It was revealed in the announcement that his contract, starting on January 1, 2014, would see him begin by traveling to [[Manchester]], England, to familiarize himself with the set-up of the franchise owners.<ref name=\"Kreis\" /> Kreis' official unveiling was made at a press conference on January 10, 2014, where he made it public that his former assistant [[Miles Joseph]] had joined him at the club.<ref name=\"press conference\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2014/January/Press-conference? |title=Jason Kreis Head Coach Press Conference |date=January 10, 2014 |work=nycfc.com |access-date=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2014, the club announced that Spanish [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]-winning striker [[David Villa]] had signed as the first ever player.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nycfc.com/News/Latest%20News/2014/June/David-Villa-signs-for-NYCFC |title=David Villa signs for New York City FC \u2013 New York City FC |date=June 2, 2014 |publisher=Nycfc.com |access-date=June 2, 2014}}</ref> While the team awaited its MLS start in 2015, Villa was loaned to [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]], a club also owned by [[City Football Group]]. He was, however, called back after only four matches.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/10/22/uk-soccer-australia-villa-idUKKCN0IB0EA20141022 |title=Villa to leave Melbourne City after four games |last=Mulvenney |first=Nick |date=October 22, 2014 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=November 25, 2014}}</ref> On July 24, 2014, New York City announced at a live press conference in [[Brooklyn]] that ex-England international and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] all-time top goal scorer [[Frank Lampard]] would be joining them as their second [[Designated Player Rule|Designated Player]]. Reyna hailed Lampard as \"one of the greatest players in world history\", while Lampard stated \"it is a privilege to be able to help make history here in New York City\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2014/July/Lampard8 |title=Welcome to New York City: Frank Lampard &#124; New York City FC |last=Janine Padilla |date=July 24, 2014 |publisher=Nycfc.com |access-date=August 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/soccer-dirty-tackle/frank-lampard-unveiled-as-nycfc-s-fourth-player-on-two-year-deal-151847263.html |title=Frank Lampard unveiled as NYCFC's fourth player on two-year deal &#124; Dirty Tackle \u2013 Yahoo Sports |last=Peck |first=Brooks |date=July 24, 2014 |publisher=Yahoo! |access-date=August 11, 2014}}</ref> On July 6, 2015, the club signed ex-Italian international [[Andrea Pirlo]] from [[Juventus]] as their third Designated Player.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/07/06/andrea-pirlo-join-new-york-city-fc-third-designated-player |title=Andrea Pirlo to Join New York City FC as Third Designated Player |date=July 6, 2015 |website=New York City FC |access-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 MLS SuperDraft]], as an expansion team, New York City had second overall pick, choosing [[Oregon State Beavers men's soccer|Oregon State]] forward [[Khiry Shelton]] as their first pick.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/01/15/khiry-shelton-joins-nycfc |title=Khiry Shelton Joins NYCFC |date=January 15, 2015 |access-date=November 12, 2015 |publisher=New York City FC}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: Inaugural season and progress===\n{{main|2015 New York City FC season}}\n\nAn up-and-down pre-season saw them dominate their first ever [[exhibition match]], played against Scotland's [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], with Villa scoring the club's first ever goal in a regulated match,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/new-york-city-fc-play-5140660 |title=New York City play first ever professional match against SPL side St. Mirren |date=February 10, 2015 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |access-date=March 8, 2015}}</ref> while in the [[2015 Carolina Challenge Cup|Carolina Challenge Cup]], they finished second out of four teams after a slow start ruled out their chances of picking up the non-competitive silverware. Their first ever league game was played on March 8 against fellow expansion side [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]], with [[Mix Diskerud]] scoring their first ever competitive goal in a game which finished 1\u20131 in front of a packed [[Orlando Citrus Bowl Stadium|Citrus Bowl]] stadium.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2015/03/08/goal-mix-diskerud-scores-first-ever-mls-goal-new-york-city-fc-history? |title=GOAL: Mix Diskerud scores first ever MLS goal in New York City history |date=March 8, 2015 |website=mlssoccer.com |access-date=March 8, 2015}}</ref> A week later in their first home game, Villa and [[Patrick Mullins (soccer)|Patrick Mullins]] scored in their first home win against New England Revolution in front of a crowd of 43,507.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/new-york-city-fc/result/result-new-york-city-fc-claim-historic-first-win_211518.html |title=Result: New York City claim historic first win |last=Gorst |first=Paul |date=March 15, 2015 |work=Sports Mole |access-date=March 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/major-league-soccer/19/blog/post/2350343/new-york-city-fc-fittingly-celebrate-their-first-home-game-with-a-first-win |title=New York City fittingly celebrate their first home game with a first win |website=ESPNFC.com |access-date=May 18, 2015}}</ref> The team eventually suffered an eleven-game winless streak which ended on June 16, after defeating the [[Philadelphia Union]] 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/1110/major-league-soccer/2015/06/06/12481092/nycfc-snaps-11-game-winless-streak |title=NYCFC snaps 11 game winless streak |website=Goal.com |access-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNew York City faced the [[New York Cosmos (2010)|New York Cosmos]] in the fourth round of the [[2015 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup]], and were eliminated on penalties after playing overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/06/17/new-york-city-fc-vs-new-york-cosmos-match-recap |title=New York City vs. New York Cosmos: Match Recap |date=June 18, 2015 |website=New York City FC |access-date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> The team finished 8th in the Eastern Conference, 17th overall. After the season ended, Kreis was relieved from his head coaching duties on November 2. The team's failure to make the playoffs and the team's second lowest points in the league, were the main factors in his release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/11/02/jason-kreis-leaves-post-new-york-city-fc-head-coach |title=Jason Kreis leaves post as New York City Head Coach |date=November 2, 2015 |website=nycfc.com |access-date=November 3, 2015}}</ref> A week later, [[Patrick Vieira]] was announced as the new head coach of the team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/11/09/patrick-vieira-appointed-new-york-city-fc-head-coach |title=Patrick Vieira appointed as New York City Head Coach |date=November 9, 2015 |website=nycfc.com |access-date=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Patrick Vieira NYCFC.JPG|thumb|[[Patrick Vieira]] was the second head coach]]\nUnder Vieira's stewardship, the club had a remarkable season in 2016. The club began pre-season trading for [[Jack Harrison (footballer, born 1996)|Jack Harrison]], the first overall pick in the [[2016 MLS SuperDraft]]. Harrison made an immediate impact and became a core component of the club in his first year with the team, forming a formidable partnership with Villa. Villa also regained his striking form, eventually becoming the recipient of the league's [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|MVP Award]] after scoring 23 goals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jRiUBraCpJ4 |title=David Villa: 2016 MLS MVP |via=YouTube |publisher=MLS |access-date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> New York City qualified for the playoffs for the first time in franchise history, eventually losing to [[Toronto FC|Toronto]] in a two-game series in the Eastern Conference semi-finals. Following the season's conclusion, the club parted ways with Lampard, who had become injury prone during his time with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/english-premier-league/story/3052186/former-england-and-chelsea-midfielder-frank-lampard-announces-retirement |title=Former New York City and Chelsea midfielder Frank Lampard announces retirement |date=February 2, 2017 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref> 2017 saw a similar season, with the club replacing Lampard with the arrival of Argentine midfielder [[Maximiliano Moralez]] as their new, third Designated Player. The club, however, became runners-up for the [[2017 Major League Soccer season|2017 Supporters' Shield]], finishing the regular season with a record of 16\u20139\u20139, as well as a record points total of 57. The club again, however, were once again eliminated from the playoffs in the conference semi-finals, losing to the fifth seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] by a 4\u20133 goal aggregate.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2017-11-05-new-york-city-fc-vs-columbus-crew-sc/boxscore |title=Matchcenter |website=matchcenter.mlssoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNew York City had then utilized the following off-season in order to undertake an aggressive overhaul of the squad, with ten senior players departing, including perceived starters [[Mikey Lopez]], [[R. J. Allen]], [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Brillant]], and [[Ethan White]]. Designated Player [[Andrea Pirlo]] also departed, announcing his retirement prior to the club's final playoff game against Columbus Crew. He was then replaced with the addition of [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguayan]] international [[Jesus Medina]] on New Year's Eve, as New York City's third Designated Player. The club further began upon replacing other departing players with the promotions of both [[Jonathan Lewis (soccer)|Jonathan Lewis]], the third-overall pick in the [[2017 MLS SuperDraft]], and [[James Sands]], the club's first ever [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|Homegrown Player]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/11/27/new-york-city-fc-announce-roster-options-2018 |title=New York City Announce Roster Options for 2018 |date=November 27, 2017 |website=New York City FC |access-date=November 27, 2017}}</ref> Sands also grew up in the nearby city of [[Rye, New York]]. Soon after, 2016's Defensive Player of the Year, [[R\u00f3nald Matarrita]], extended his contract to remain with the club beyond the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2016/11/15/matarrita-named-defensive-player-2016 |title=R\u00f3nald Matarrita named DPoY for 2016 |date=November 15, 2016 |website=New York City FC |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/matarrita-signs-nycfc-contract-extension/1rmsiccm8noo21cw8taxf8jx77 |title=MATARRITA SIGNS NYC CONTRACT EXTENSION |website=New York City FC |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> The club then made its first acquisition on December 13, with the signing of defender [[Anton Tinnerholm]], who joined from [[Allsvenskan]] champions [[Malm\u00f6 FF|Malm\u00f6]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/12/11/report-nycfc-sign-swedish-right-back-anton-tinnerholm |title=Report: NYCFC sign Swedish right back Anton Tinnerholm |date=December 11, 2017 |website=MLS |access-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref> Tinnerholm, a [[Sweden national football team|Swedish]] international, is typically deployed as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]]. The team then acquired another right-back in the form of [[Saad Abdul-Salaam]] in a trade with [[Sporting Kansas City]], trading former second overall pick [[Khiry Shelton]], largely considered a [[Draft (sports)#Other terminology|bust]], on December 14.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/post/2017/12/14/sporting-kc-acquires-forward-khiry-shelton-trade-new-york-city-fc |title=Sporting KC acquires forward Khiry Shelton in trade with New York City |date=December 14, 2017 |website=SKC |access-date=December 14, 2017}}</ref> The club then rounded out the roster with a trio of internationals, as striker [[Jo Inge Berget]], central defender [[C\u00e9dric Hountondji]], and speedster [[Ismael Tajouri-Shradi]] all joined the team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/01/19/new-york-city-fc-signs-jo-inge-berget |title=New York City sign striker Berget |date=January 12, 2018 |publisher=NYCFC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/01/11/new-york-city-fc-sign-defender-cedric-hountondji |title=New York City sign defender Hountondji |date=January 12, 2018 |publisher=MLS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/01/12/new-york-city-fc-sign-attacker-ismael-tajouri-austria-wien |title=New York City sign attacker Ismael Tajouri from Austria Wien |date=January 12, 2018 |publisher=NYCFC}}</ref> [[Brad Stuver]] was also acquired in a trade with Columbus, in order to provide cover as third-choice goalkeeper.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2017/12/14/news-crew-sc-acquires-2019-superdraft-pick-trade-new-york-city-fc |title=Crew acquires 2019 SuperDraft pick via trade with New York City |date=December 14, 2017 |website=columbuscrewsc.com |publisher=MLS |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> Finally, Ghanaian international [[Ebenezer Ofori]] joined on loan from [[Bundesliga]] side [[VfB Stuttgart]], while the club selected goalkeeper Jeff Caldwell with the nineteenth overall pick in the [[2018 MLS SuperDraft]], as they began the season in search of a [[2018 Major League Soccer season|MLS Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/02/21/new-york-city-fc-signs-ebenezer-ofori |title=New York City sign Ebenezer Ofori |date=February 21, 2018 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=March 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/02/28/new-york-city-fc-signs-jeff-caldwell |title=New York City signs Jeff Caldwell |date=February 28, 2018 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=March 3, 2018}}</ref> The team also conducted business through the season, as they signed [[Sebastien Ibeagha]], a defender who last played for affiliate club [[San Antonio FC|San Antonio]], after he impressed following a trial.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/02/27/new-york-city-fc-sign-sebastien-ibeagha-usl-affiliate-san-antonio-fc |title=New York City sign Sebastien Ibeagha from USL affiliate San Antonio |date=February 27, 2018 |website=mlssoccer.com |publisher=MLS |access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:David Villa NYCFC vs. Houston Dynamo- 5-30-2015 (18289895465).jpg|thumb|upright|[[David Villa]] is the club's all-time top goalscorer.]]\nMidway through the season, however, Vieira would depart the club to return to France, in order to coach at [[Ligue 1]] club [[OGC Nice|Nice]]. His tenure saw the team adopt a free-flowing, attacking, [[Glossary of association football terms#P|press-based]] system, which gained both the team and coach several plaudits from experts, players, and fellow coaches.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theathletic.com/386866/2018/06/09/patrick-vieira-and-nycfc-are-denied-their-storybook-ending/ |title=Patrick Vieira and NYC are denied their storybook ending |website=TheAthletic |access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2017/08/12/vieiras-value-going-beyond-coaching-for-nycfc-mls/ |title=Vieira's value going beyond coaching for New York City |date=August 12, 2017 |website=New York Post |access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.footballwhispers.com/blog/vieira-becoming-golden-boy-mls-coaching |title=Vieira becoming the golden boy for MLS coaches |website=FootballWhispers |access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cybrown/2018/05/08/patrick-vieira-would-be-more-than-a-sentimental-pick-for-the-arsenal-job/ |title=Vieira Would Be More Than a Sentimental Pick for Arsenal Job |website=Forbes |access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref> He departed alongside his band of assistant coaches: Christian Lattanzio, Kristian Wilson and Matt Cook.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/first-team/first-team-news/2018/june/patrick-vieira-nycfc-nice-leaving |title=Patrick Vieira departs New York City to join Nice |publisher=Manchester City F.C.  |access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> Vieira was then quickly replaced by Dom\u00e8nec Torrent, [[Pep Guardiola]]'s long-term assistant coach.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/new-york-city-fc/17606/blog/post/3522795/nycfc-put-faith-in-cfg-institution-in-replacing-patrick-vieira-with-domenec-torrent |title=NYC put faith in City Football Group institution in replacing Vieira with Torrent |date=June 11, 2018 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref> Torrent was successful in his first game, securing a 2\u20131 win at home against Toronto on June 24. The club then added to their roster during the season, with free agent [[Eloi Amagat|Eloi]] joining as Torrent's first signing, who arrived from sister club [[Girona FC|Girona]] on July 25.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2018/07/25/domenec-torrent-summons-old-face-for-first-nycfc-signing/ |title=Torrent summons old face for first New York City signing |work=New York Post |access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref> The team then concluded a loan deal for youth prospect [[Valent\u00edn Castellanos]] two days later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/07/27/new-york-city-fc-sign-argentine-attacking-mid-valentin-castellanos-loan |title=NYC sign Valentin Castellanos on loan |date=July 27, 2018 |publisher=MLS |access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref> Castellanos would score on his debut on August 4. Despite this, Torrent's bright start would eventually fade, and he could only register an additional six victories to close the season, including a period of one win in two months. New York City would eventually qualify for the playoffs as the third seed in the Eastern Conference, but again, were defeated in the second round to conclude the 2018 season. Individually, Moralez shone, and was voted an [[2019 MLS All-Star Game|All-Star]] for his performances.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/all-star/2019/rosters/mls-all-star-team |title=2019 MLS All-Star Roster |date=June 20, 2019 |website=[[Major League Soccer]] |access-date=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe club then underwent another period of transition in the off-season, with several players' options declined on November 29, including cult-hero [[Tommy McNamara]], recent signings Ofori and Eloi, and first team regulars [[Maxime Chanot]] and [[Rodney Wallace (footballer)|Rodney Wallace]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.prosoccerusa.com/mls/new-york-city-fc/nycfc-original-tommy-mcnamara-among-7-players-with-contract-options-declined/ |title=New York City decline options of seven players |date=November 29, 2018 |publisher=ProSoccerUSA |access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref> Moreover, Berget's contract with the club was mutually terminated, after just a single season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/01/25/new-york-city-fc-and-jo-inge-berget-mutually-terminate-contract |title=New York City and Jo Inge Berget Mutually Terminate Contract |date=January 25, 2019 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref> The club also parted ways with record appearance maker and goalscorer Villa\u2014who had been voted into the [[MLS Best XI]] twice and was a four-time [[MLS All-Star]] in his four seasons with New York\u2014who joined [[J-League]] side [[Vissel Kobe]]. Later, an option to buy was exercised in Castellanos' loan deal to make his transfer permanent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/3714182/david-villa-to-join-andres-iniesta-at-vissel-kobe-after-leaving-new-york-city-fc |title=David Villa leaves New York City to join Japanese side Vissel Kobe |date=December 2018 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/11/29/chanot-and-mcnamara-declined-nycfc-continue-change |title=New York City sign Valent\u00edn Castellanos |date=November 29, 2018 |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref> Chanot was eventually resigned to a multi-year contract on December 8, while Ofori's loan was extended for another season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/12/08/maxime-chanot-signs-new-multi-year-contract-new-york-city-fc |title=Maxime Chanot Signs New Multi-Year Contract with New York City |date=December 8, 2018 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/01/22/nycfc-re-acquire-ebenezer-ofori-loan |title=New York City re-acquire midfielder Ebenezer Ofori on loan from Stuttgart |date=January 22, 2019 |publisher=MLS |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> New York City made their first acquisition, [[Tony Rocha]], just under a week later in a trade with [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]], whereby the team parted with a fourth-round pick in the [[2019 MLS SuperDraft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/12/12/orlando-city-sc-trade-midfielder-tony-rocha-new-york-city-fc |title=Orlando City trade midfielder Tony Rocha to New York City |date=December 12, 2018 |publisher=MLS |access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> The club later loaned in U.S. international [[Keaton Parks]] in January, who joined from Portuguese side [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/01/19/new-york-city-fc-acquire-keaton-parks |title=New York City acquire Keaton Parks |date=January 19, 2019 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> while [[Juan Pablo Torres (soccer)|Juan Pablo Torres]] joined from [[Belgian Pro League]] side [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|Lokeren]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/01/26/new-york-city-fc-sign-juan-pablo-torres |title=New York City sign Juan Pablo Torres |date=January 26, 2019 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=January 26, 2019}}</ref> Meanwhile, Justin Haak was promoted to the senior team as the club's second Homegrown Player. Hountondji was later waived in order to clear a roster spot for the club's 12th overall draft pick in the 2019 MLS SuperDraft, goalkeeper Luis Barraza.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/01/28/new-york-city-fc-waives-cedric-hountondji |title=New York City waive Hountondji, Barraza signs |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=January 29, 2018}}</ref> New York City then signed Romanian international [[Alexandru Mitri\u021b\u0103]] as the club's third Designated Player on February 4, for a rumored club-record transfer fee of [[United States dollar|US$]]9.1 million, making him also one of the most expensive transfers in MLS history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/02/04/welcomealexandru-nycfc-sign-romanian-international-alexandru-mitri |title=#WelcomeAlexandru &#124; New York City Sign Alexandru Mitri\u021b\u0103 |date=February 4, 2019 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ziare.com/liga-1/stiri-liga-i/mitrita-in-topul-celor-mai-scumpi-jucatori-din-istoria-ligii-1-iata-cati-bani-a-incasat-craiova-1548484 |title=Mitrita, in topul celor mai scumpi jucatori din istoria Ligii 1: Iata cati bani a incasat Craiova |date=February 4, 2019 |publisher=Ziare.com |language=Romanian |trans-title=Mitri\u021b\u0103, at the top of the most expensive players in the history of Liga 1: The sum earned by Craiova |access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref> The club later signed Brazilian forward [[H\u00e9ber Araujo dos Santos|H\u00e9ber]] on March 21, and in June, signed Scottish forward [[Gary Mackay-Steven]] on a free transfer from [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].\n\nMid-season, the club traded for defender [[Eric Miller (soccer)|Eric Miller]] from [[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]] on July 29, for $50,000 in general [[allocation money]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/07/29/new-york-city-fc-acquires-defender-eric-miller-minnesota-united |title=New York City FC Acquires Defender Eric Miller from Minnesota United &#124; New York City FC |date=July 29, 2019}}</ref> Despite these roster changes, the team again failed in the playoffs, falling to previous [[MLS Cup]] champions [[Toronto FC|Toronto]], despite the club finishing atop the regular season standings in Eastern Conference for the first time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://heraldpublicist.com/tfc-beats-nycfc-to-reach-eastern-conference-final/ |title=Toronto beats New York to reach Eastern Conference Finals |publisher=Herald Publicist |access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> Following this, the club \"mutually parted ways\" with head coach Torrent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/11/08/nycfc-head-coach-dome-torrent-mutually-agree-part-ways |title=NYC, Torrent mutually part ways |date=November 8, 2019 |publisher=MLS |access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The club announced its end of season awards on November 12, with Chanot receiving Defensive Player of the Year,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4xfkh-JFei/ |title=Chanot receives New York City Defensive Player of the Year |publisher=Instagram |access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> while H\u00e9ber won Newcomer of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4vJj0UnC3l/ |title=H\u00e9ber receives New York City Newcomer of the Year |publisher=Instagram |access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Moralez again shone in New York for a second successive season, being voted into the 2019 [[MLS Best XI]]. \n\nAt the start of the off-season, the team oversaw a number of departures; veteran defender [[Ben Sweat]] left after being selected by upstart MLS club [[Inter Miami CF|Inter Miami]] as their first overall pick in the [[2019 MLS Expansion Draft]], while Sporting Director [[Claudio Reyna]] also left the club, joining expansion side [[Austin FC|Austin]]. Reyna was replaced by the in-house promotion of Technical Director David Lee, who assumed the role as Sporting Director.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/11/21/claudio-reyna-departs-new-york-city-fc-join-austin-fc-technical-director-david-lee |title=Claudio Reyna Departs New York City to Join Austin; Technical Director David Lee Promoted to Sporting Director |date=November 21, 2019 |publisher=NYCFC |access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Moreover, the club also announced Homegrown Player [[Joe Scally]] would depart to join [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]], effective January 1, 2021. The official transfer fee was undisclosed, although, multiple reports suggested the fee is to be a seven-figure sum that could rise to become one of the highest transfer fees received for a player in MLS history.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2019/11/13/nycfc-homegrown-joe-scally-join-borussia-monchengladbach-2021 |title=NYCFC Homegrown Joe Scally to Join Borussia Monchengladbach in 2021 &#124; New York City |date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> Soon thereafter, Parks' loan was made permanent,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2020/01/08/new-york-city-fc-permanently-acquires-keaton-parks-sl-benfica |title=New York City Permanently Acquires Keaton Parks from S.L. Benfica |date=January 8, 2020}}</ref> while the club completed the acquisition of [[Gedion Zelalem]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2020/01/11/new-york-city-fc-signs-midfielder-gedion-zelalem |title=New York City Signs Midfielder Gedion Zelalem |date=January 11, 2020 |website=nycfc.com |access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> On January 28, 2020, New York City signed Icelandic midfielder [[Gu\u00f0mundur \u00de\u00f3rarinsson]] from Swedish club [[IFK Norrk\u00f6ping|Norrk\u00f6ping]], and the club announced the appointment of [[Ronny Deila]] as the new head coach; Deila signed a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronny Deila Named New York City Head Coach |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2020/01/06/ronny-deila-named-new-york-city-fc-head-coach |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=New York City FC |date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nNew York City began the 2020 season with their debut in the [[CONCACAF Champions League]], and advanced to the [[2020_CONCACAF_Champions_League#Quarter-finals|quarter finals]] after defeating Costa Rican outfit [[A.D. San Carlos|San Carlos]] 6\u20133 over two legs. The club then began the [[2020 MLS season]] with a defeat, losing 1\u20130 away against [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus]]. New York City subsequently announced the signing of Uruguayan midfielder [[Nicol\u00e1s Acevedo]] from [[Liverpool F.C. (Montevideo)|Liverpool Montevideo]] on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York City Acquire Nicol\u00e1s Acevedo From Liverpool Montevideo |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2020/03/02/nycfc-permanently-acquires-nicol-s-acevedo-uruguayan-club-liverpool-fc |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |work=New York City FC |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Colors and badge ==\n{{Commons|New York City FC kits}}\n[[File:Logo New York City FC.png|thumb|150px|The badge used at the launch of the club]]\n\nWith the team announced in 2013, almost two years before it was due to play its first competitive game in 2015, the board of the nascent New York club announced their intention to take their time in building the club, and at the team's launch ceremony did not unveil colors or a badge, instead only using a placeholder image of a blue circle with \"New York City FC\" written within.\n\nAlthough club chairman [[Ferran Soriano]] emphasized the desire to create a club with its own identity, rather than relying entirely on the brands of club owners [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and the [[New York Yankees]], the online presence that the club kept up across its own website and on various social networking websites maintained a consistent approach of using the sky blue of the Manchester club and the navy blue of the [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] team, along with the white employed by both owner-clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theroar.com.au/2014/01/24/facelift-needed-for-melbourne-heart-to-start-again/ |title=Facelift needed for Melbourne Heart to start again |date=January 24, 2014 |website=theroar.au |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> With the soccer side running the operations of New York City, however, the vast majority of journalistic reporting and speculation assumed that the club's color-scheme would eventually be revealed as a reflection of, if not a copy of Manchester City's sky blue kits with white trim,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nextimpulsesports.com/2013/05/21/new-york-gets-second-mls-franchise-nycfc/ |title=New York Gets Second MLS Franchise: NYCFC |date=May 21, 2013 |website=nextimpulsesports.com |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ex-us-captain-reyna-direct-nyc-soccer-team |title=EX-US CAPTAIN REYNA TO DIRECT NYC SOCCER TEAM |date=May 22, 2013 |agency=Associated Press |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> with Director of Football Operations [[Claudio Reyna]] saying at the press conference announcing his appointment that he was \"excited to again wear City's \u2018Sky Blue\u2019 as part of the expansion of the MLS\".<ref name=\"MLS-reyna\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://the11.ca/2013/05/22/nycfc-announcement-leaves-more-questions-than-answers-and-thats-good-for-mls/ |title=NYCFC announcement leaves more questions than answers \u2013 and that's good for MLS |date=May 22, 2013 |website=the11.ca |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307230116/http://the11.ca/2013/05/22/nycfc-announcement-leaves-more-questions-than-answers-and-thats-good-for-mls/ |archive-date=March 7, 2014 |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHaving allowed the speculation and amateur designs to build interest in the club for almost nine months, on February 4, 2014 it was announced that the selection of an official club badge was to be forthcoming, with the club planning to release two designs for the crest in two different styles, which would then be put to a public vote to select the chosen design.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/debut-crest-through-22915/ |title=New York City F.C. to debut crest through the fans |date=February 4, 2014 |website=Empire of Soccer |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> In the meantime, New York City's official website announced a \"Badge of Badges\" campaign, inviting all to create their own crests on a hosted badge-designer page, with every entry ultimately to be incorporated into a mosaic of the badge when a final design was selected, the mosaic to be available both online and in physical form at the club's training ground once built.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2014/February/Badge-of-badges |title=Badge of badges |date=February 4, 2014 |website=nycfc.com |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough March 3 was originally set as the release date for the two proposed logos, the vote was pushed back as the Yankees vetoed one of the potential crests for infringing their own trademark.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/yankees-trademark-concerns-23773/ |title=Yankees Trademark Concerns Delay NYCFC Logo Launch |date=March 4, 2014 |website=Empire of Soccer |access-date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> The two badge options, both designed by Rafael Esquer following the success of his [[Made in NY]] mark, were revealed on March 10.  At that time, the club's official color scheme of navy blue, sky blue and orange was also announced.  The orange was an homage to [[New Amsterdam|the city's Dutch heritage]], and is the same shade found in [[Flag of New York City|the city's flag]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/speaking-rafael-creator-24018/ |title=Speaking to Rafael Esquer, Creator of the NYCFC badges |date=March 12, 2013 |website=empireofsoccer.com |access-date=March 21, 2014}}</ref> Fans were given three days to vote on the final design, and the winner was announced on March 20.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2014/March/Badge-vote? |title=Vote Now: It's up to you, New York |date=March 10, 2014 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=March 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/03/20/new-york-city-fc-official-badge |title=New York City FC Official Badge |date=March 20, 2014 |access-date=November 18, 2016 |publisher=New York City FC}}</ref>\n\nAt an event at [[Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan|Hell's Kitchen]] in Manhattan on November 13, 2014, thousands of fans and media were on hand to see New York City unveil its inaugural jersey.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/unveil-announce-sponsorship-30136/ |title=NYCFC unveil new home kit, announce Etihad sponsorship |last=Martinez |first=Dave |publisher=Empire of Soccer |access-date=March 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/11/13/new-york-city-fc-unveils-first-home-jersey |title=New York City FC Unveils First Home Jersey |date=November 13, 2014 |access-date=November 13, 2014 |publisher=New York City FC}}</ref> The away jersey was revealed on November 24, a black shirt with sky blue and orange trim and five reflective black stripes to represent the five boroughs of the city.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/11/24/nycfcrevealed-complete-look |title=#NYCFCRevealed: The Complete Look |date=November 24, 2014 |website=nycfc.com |access-date=November 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor the club's second season, a new away uniform was unveiled, featuring shirt, shorts and socks all of navy blue trimmed in orange.  The shirt was dominated by lighter-blue concentric circles radiating out from the logo that \"celebrate the energy of New York City\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2016/02/10/new-york-city-fc-reveals-new-2016-secondary-jersey |title=New York City FC Reveals New 2016 Secondary Jersey |date=February 10, 2016 |website=NYCFC.com |publisher=New York City Football Club |access-date=February 22, 2017}}</ref> The home uniform remained virtually unchanged, with sky blue socks substituting for the white.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/photo/2016/02/10/2016-mls-jerseys-uniforms-kits-critique |title=Critiquing the 2016 MLS uniforms |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=March 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2017, the club unveiled its second-ever home uniform, pairing the sky blue shirt with navy blue shorts. A small [[Flags of New York City|New York City flag]] is on the front of the shirt.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/02/07/new-york-city-fc-reveals-new-2017-home-uniform |title=New York City FC Reveals New 2017 Home Uniform |date=February 7, 2017 |website=NYCFC.com |publisher=New York City Football Club |access-date=February 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe club's third away uniform was unveiled on February 7, 2018.  The kit is primarily gray with sky blue details, \"inspired by the concrete jungle that is the Big Apple\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/02/07/everywherewego-new-york-city-fc-unveil-new-2018-away-jersey |title=#EverywhereWeGo: New York City FC unveil new 2018 away jersey |last=Booth |first=Mark |date=February 7, 2018 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/gallery/behind-scenes-photos-nycfcs-2018-away-kit-unveiling |title=Behind the scenes photos of NYCFC's 2018 away kit unveiling |date=February 7, 2018 |website=fourfourtwo.com |publisher=FourFourTwo |access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Kit suppliers and shirt sponsors ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\"|Season\n!style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\"|Manufacturer\n!style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\"|Sponsor\n!style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\"|Ref.\n|-\n| 2015\u2013present\n| [[Adidas]]\n| [[Etihad Airways]]\n| <ref name=\"Etihad\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/11/12/new-york-city-football-club-takes-flight-etihad-airways-partnership |title=New York City Football Club Takes Flight with Etihad Airways Partnership |date=November 13, 2014 |publisher=nycfc.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113184154/http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/11/12/new-york-city-football-club-takes-flight-etihad-airways-partnership |archive-date=November 13, 2014 |access-date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n[[City Football Group]] sponsor [[Etihad Airways]] was announced to be New York City's inaugural jersey sponsor in an event at [[Terminal 5 (venue)|Terminal 5]] on November 13, 2014, at the same event which revealed the club's first ever jersey design.<ref name=\"Etihad\" /> The announcement capped a week in which [[Heineken]] and [[Adidas]] had also been signed up as secondary sponsors of the club.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/11/10/new-york-city-fc-adds-adidas-official-partner |title=New York City FC Adds adidas as Official Partner |date=November 10, 2014 |publisher=nycfc.com |access-date=November 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/11/12/new-york-city-fc-joins-heineken-roster |title=New York City FC Joins Heineken Roster |date=November 12, 2014 |publisher=nycfc.com |access-date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcasting ==\nIn one of the club's first announcements on October 3, 2013 \u2013 before announcing where the team would play and before any players had been signed \u2013 New York City signed an agreement with [[WFAN (AM)|WFAN]] to broadcast English-language radio commentary to the New York area for club games and also serves as the flagship station of the 'New York City FC Radio Network', powered by [[CBS]].<ref name=\"WFAN\" /> A year later, on December 18, 2014, the club announced that it was following up its radio deal with an agreement with the [[YES Network]] to televise all home and away games.<ref name=\"YES\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2014/12/18/nycfc-and-yes-announce-multi-year-agreement |title=NYCFC and YES Announce Multi-Year Agreement |date=December 18, 2014 |website=nycfc.com |access-date=December 18, 2014}}</ref> On top of the YES broadcasting rights, the deal included free streaming of all games across the internet via the [[Fox Sports Go]] website.<ref name=\"YES\" /> With club co-owners the [[New York Yankees]] also part-owners of YES, the deals were of little surprise, with even Yankees president [[Randy Levine]] openly speculating on the possibility within days of the club's unveiling.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/05/21/new-york-city-fc-matches-televised-yes-network-yankees-ownership-stake-will- |title=New York City FC matches televised on YES Network? Yankees ownership stake will bring synergies |date=May 21, 2013 |website=mlssoccer.com |access-date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nGames were broadcast on radio by WFAN and [[WNYM]] during the team's first season; the games were available via webstream for the subsequent two seasons. Broadcasts returned to terrestrial radio in 2018, as [[noncommercial educational|noncommercial]] [[WNYE (FM)|WNYE]] became the team's flagship audio outlet.<ref name=\"nycf_Grou\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/03/02/groundbreaking-radio-partnership-announced |title=Groundbreaking Radio Partnership Announced |date=March 2, 2018 |website=New York City FC |access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Spanish-language radio station [[WEPN (AM)|WEPN]] began to broadcast New York City games, with play-by-play from announcer Roberto Abramowitz and color commentary from Ariel Judas.{{citation needed|date=April 2019|reason=A source other than the station itself would be best here}}\n\n== Stadium ==\n{{main|Yankee Stadium|New York City FC Stadium}}\n\n[[File:Soccer at Yankee Stadium, August 2012.jpg|thumb|The team currently plays at Yankee Stadium.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|Name\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|Location\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|Years\n|-\n| [[Yankee Stadium]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|The Bronx, New York\n| 2015\u2013present\n|-\n| [[Coffey Field]]\n|  2016; 1 match in U.S. Open Cup<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/cosmos-beat-nycfc-kings-new-york-soccer-article-1.2675693 |title=Cosmos beat NYCFC again in U.S. Open Cup, want to be 'kings of New York' soccer |date=June 16, 2016 |website=Daily News|location=New York |access-date=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Pratt & Whitney Stadium at Rentschler Field]]\n| [[East Hartford, Connecticut]]\n|  2017; 1 home regular season match\n|-\n| [[Citi Field]]\n| [[Queens, New York]]\n| {{plainlist|\n* 2017; 1 home regular season match\n* 2019; 1 home match MLS playoffs\n* 2020; 4 home regular season matches\n|-\n| [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]]\n| [[Harrison, New Jersey]]\n| 2020; 1 home [[CONCACAF Champions League]] match<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/05/why-nycfc-will-be-hosting-home-game-at-red-bulls-arena/|title=Why NYCFC will be hosting \u2018home game\u2019 at Red Bull Arena|newspaper=New York Post|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\nOn April 21, 2014, the club confirmed that they would play their first season home games at Yankee Stadium, and that plans for a future stadium were in progress.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FtsNq7RgZT4 |title=New York City FC Major Announcement |date=April 12, 2014 |via=YouTube |access-date=April 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBefore the official team was announced, plans were presented by MLS to build a soccer stadium in [[Flushing Meadows\u2013Corona Park]] in [[Queens]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/06/sports/soccer/mls-sets-sights-on-team-and-stadium-in-queens.html |title=M.L.S. Promotes Stadium at a Town Hall Meeting |last=David Picker |date=December 5, 2012 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 22, 2013}}</ref> However, due to opposition to building a stadium on park land as well as objections from the [[New York Mets]], who play nearby, the site lost favor once the new team was announced. The team came up with an alternate proposal to build the stadium in [[the Bronx]] adjacent to [[Yankee Stadium]] to be completed in 2018 at the earliest.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/favorable-returns-stadium-22856/ |title=Favorable returns for NYCFC after stadium Town Hall |last=Dave Martinez |date=February 1, 2014 |work=empireofsoccer.com |access-date=March 22, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, New York property lawyer Martin Edelman, a member of [[Manchester City FC|Manchester City]]'s board of directors, said that New York City had abandoned plans for the Bronx site.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/usa/11464640/New-York-City-FCs-home-truth-Yankee-Stadium-will-never-be-their-field-of-dreams.html |title=New York City FC's home truth: Yankee Stadium will never be their field of dreams |last=Williams |first=Bob |date=March 13, 2015 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=August 23, 2017}}</ref> On August 17, 2017, the club's architects attended a site visit of [[Belmont Park]] on [[Long Island]] held by the [[Empire State Development Corporation]] for parties interested in developing land adjacent to the racetrack.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/nycfcs-architects-visited-belmont-site-64411/ |title=NYCFC's Architects Visited Belmont Site |date=August 19, 2017 |website=empireofsoccer.com |access-date=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nClub president [[Jon Patricof]] confirmed in September 2017 that the franchise \"(has) multiple sites under active consideration \u2013 some involve public processes and some are private.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2017/09/16/nycfc-remain-in-active-search-for-new-home/ |title=NYCFC remain in active search for new home |last=Schnitzer |first=Kyle |date=September 16, 2017 |work=The New York Post |access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> On September 25, 2017, it was reported that the club would submit a proposal to build a soccer-specific stadium on the {{convert|43|acre|adj=on}} site at Belmont Park.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/soccer/source-nycfc-will-bid-to-build-soccer-stadium-at-belmont-park-1.14271274 |title=Source: NYCFC will bid to build soccer stadium at Belmont Park |date=September 25, 2017 |work=Newsday |access-date=September 25, 2017}}</ref> On December 19, 2017, the site at Belmont Park was selected by the Empire State Development Corporation for the [[New York Islanders]]' new 18,000 seat arena, ending the club's pursuit of a soccer-specific stadium at the site.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/hockey/islanders/islanders-new-arena-belmont-park-1.15519161 |title=Sources: Islanders' arena bid picked for Belmont Park |date=December 19, 2017 |website=Newsday |access-date=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, New York City played a home match at [[Pratt & Whitney Stadium at Rentschler Field]] in [[East Hartford, Connecticut]], {{convert|107|mi|km}} from the city, due to a scheduling conflict with a rescheduled Yankees game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/08/22/nycfcs-home-game-vs-houston-dynamo-relocated-pratt-whitney-stadium |title=NYCFC's Home Game vs Houston Dynamo Relocated to Pratt & Whitney Stadium |date=August 22, 2017 |access-date=August 22, 2017 |publisher=New York City FC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/new-york-city-fc-forced-to-move-home-game-to-east-hartford/brr0v8sn03ve1vn0y5jwzggbi |title=New York City FC Forced to Move Home Game to East Hartford, Conn. |date=August 22, 2017 |work=Goal.com |access-date=August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2017, New York City played their final regular season home match at Queens' [[Citi Field]], home of the [[New York Mets]], due to another scheduling conflict with a Yankees [[American League Championship Series]] game at Yankee Stadium.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/10/12/new-york-city-fc-announces-venue-change-final-game-2017-regular-season |title=New York City FC Announces Venue Change for Final Game of 2017 Regular Season |date=October 12, 2017 |publisher=New York City FC |access-date=October 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, new plans for the [[Harlem River Yards]] development in the south Bronx were revealed, for the land north of the [[Willis Avenue Bridge]]; the area would be anchored by the new stadium of 26,000 seats, which would be designed by [[Rafael Vi\u00f1oly]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2018/04/exclusive-reveal-for-700-million-harlem-river-yards-mega-project.html |title=Exclusive Reveal For $700 Million Harlem River Yards Mega-Project, Including New York's First Soccer Stadium Designed By Rafael Vi\u00f1oly |last=Fedak |first=Nikolai |date=April 17, 2018 |website=New York YIMBY |access-date=April 17, 2018}}</ref> On April 25, 2018, it was reported by club president Jon Patricof that the club is focusing on other sites more seriously than Harlem Yards. \"We submitted something to the State [of New York] as part of a request for expressions of interest,\" said Patricof about the Harlem River Yards site. \"But that's it. That site is not an active site.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://soccerstadiumdigest.com/2018/04/club-president-nycfc-is-still-searching-for-stadium-site/ |title=Club President: NYCFC is Still Searching for Stadium Site |date=April 25, 2018 |website=soccerstadiumdigest.com |access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n=== Supporters ===\nNew York City's official supporter group, [[Third Rail (MLS supporters association)|The Third Rail]], began to form after the club's announcement in May 2013, when fans met through social media, and through member drives and viewing parties for [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] matches. It had registered 1,600 members before the team's first season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/01/nyregion/a-decision-for-soccer-fans-new-york-city-football-club-or-red-bulls.html |title=Whose Side Are You On? A Decision for Soccer Fans: New York City Football Club or Red Bulls |last=Klein |first=Jeff Z. |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=May 4, 2016}}</ref> Although the group operates independently from the club, it was recognized as the official supporter group and has received exclusive access to one section in Yankee Stadium. Then-group president Chance Michaels said the name reflected the group's desire to \"power NYCFC\" the way the [[third rail]] powered the [[New York City Subway]] system.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/700-soccer-fans-and-counting-fan-club-third-rail-builds-ranks-1409880714 |title=700 Soccer Fans and Counting: Fan Club Third Rail Builds Ranks |last=Wallerson |first=Ryan |date=September 4, 2014 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=September 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBefore the club began play in March 2015, the club's season-ticket membership had already surpassed 14,000,<ref>[http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/02/26/new-york-city-fc-surpass-14000-season-tickets-inaugural-season \"New York City FC surpass 14,000 season tickets for inaugural season\"], NYCFC.com, February 26, 2015.</ref> and by April 2015 season-ticket sales had reached 16,000.<ref>[http://www.socceramerica.com/article/63215/nycfc-hits-16000-mark-in-season-ticket-sales.html \"NYCFC hits 16,000 mark in season-ticket sales\"], Soccer America, Ridge Mahoney, April 8, 2015.</ref> In October of that year, the club announced that it had sold 20,000 season tickets for the inaugural season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/10/23/new-york-city-fc-reach-20000-founding-members |title=New York City FC Reach 20,000 Founding Members |date=October 23, 2015 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City Football Club |access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2017, NYCSC (New York City Supporters Club) was recognized as the club's second official supporters group.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/nyc-supporters-club |title=New York City Supporters Club |date=May 15, 2017 |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>{{non-primary source needed|date=January 2018}} On February 13, 2020, NYCFC officially parted ways with NYCSC.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Rivalries ===\n{{main|Hudson River Derby}}\n<!-- Despite the club being relatively new, the team has rivalries with the [[New York Red Bulls]], with whom they will play the inaugural [[New York Derby (MLS)|New York Derby]], and [[Orlando City SC]], whom they joined MLS with in 2015. The latter has been particularly heated between fans of the clubs, mostly due in part to the vast differences in which they were founded. Orlando City was formerly a [[Orlando City SC (2010\u201314)|USL Pro club]], while New York City was the brainchild of both the [[New York Yankees]] and Premier League team [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], two of the most prestigious and divisive sports franchises in the of the world. -->\n\nIn May 2015, the [[New York metropolitan area]] experienced a genuine [[local derby]] in MLS league play for the first time, when New York City played their first game against the [[New York Red Bulls]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/12/11/new-york-red-bulls-sporting-director-andy-roxburgh-says-impending-rivalry-ny |title=New York Red Bulls' Andy Roxburgh says impending rivalry with New York City FC a good thing |last=Panizo |first=Franco |date=December 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/11/new-york-soccer-rivalry-already-brewing/ |title=New York Soccer Rivalry Already Brewing |last=Lewis |first=Brian |date=December 11, 2013 |work=[[New York Post]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2013/05/23/kick-new-york-city-fc-red-bulls-rivalry-heating-already |title=New York City FC, Red Bulls rivalry heating up already |last=Prince-Wright |first=Joe |date=May 23, 2013}}</ref> Although initially regarded as a manufactured rivalry with little of the traditional banter apparent between long-time local rivals,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/soccer/red-bulls-nycfc-rivalry-hype-substance-article-1.2216286 |title=Red Bulls-NYCFC rivalry more hype than substance so far |last=Bondy |first=Stefan |date=August 10, 2015 |work=Daily News|location=New York |access-date=May 9, 2015 }}</ref> the first meetings between the two clubs displayed an increasing level of animosity between the two sides.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33848142 |title=New York Red Bulls v New York City: Hudson derby heats up |date=August 10, 2015 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> The Red Bulls won the first ever encounter between the two, a league game on May 10, 2015, at Red Bull Arena.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2015-05-10-new-york-red-bulls-vs-new-york-city-fc/boxscore |title=New York Red Bulls v New York City FC |date=May 11, 2015 |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> A series of brawls between supporters of the two teams occurred before and after matches between the two teams.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireofsoccer.com/behind-between-supporters-38523/ |title=Behind The Bello's Brawl Between NYCFC, RBNY Supporters |last=Martinez |first=Dave |date=August 10, 2015 |publisher=Empire of Soccer |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> The contest has been dubbed the [[Hudson River Derby]] by supporters.\n\n=== Social media campaigns ===\nIn 2015, MLS hosted a contest between New York City and New York Red Bulls ahead of the Hudson River Derby on June 28. The team with the most votes would have the Empire State Building lit up in their favor. New York City, with over 1 million [[Facebook]] followers, launched the 'WINNYCFC' campaign on the platform and won the contest.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nycfc.com/winnycfc |title=Light The Empire State Building in New York City FC Blue |date=June 24, 2015 |work=nycfc.com/ |access-date=June 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/06/27/mls-rivalry-week-empire-state-building-turns-blue-new-york-city-fc-win-fan-vote |title=MLS Rivalry Week: Empire State Building turns blue as New York City FC win fan vote |date=June 28, 2015 |website=MLSsoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=November 9, 2016}}</ref> In the 2016 MLS season, the club started the 'We Are One' campaign on social media, followed by the 'Support Your City' campaign during the playoffs later that year.\n\n== Players and staff ==\n=== Roster ===\n{{updated|March 3, 2020|<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/players |title=First Team}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2018/03/01/official-2018-nycfc-squad-numbers-confirmed |title=Official: 2018 NYCFC Squad Numbers Confirmed |date=March 2018}}</ref>}}\n<!-- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n -- Do NOT add new players before their signing is officially announced by the club\n -- Do NOT assign unreferenced squad numbers as well.\n -- Do NOT create articles for brand new signings until they make either their MLS or U.S. Open Cup debut,\n \u2013- Do not add Wikilinks to these players as it prevents the creation of articles by people who don't understand the WP:FOOTY notability guidelines\n \u2013 Players with international caps should NOT be bolded \u2013 as per Wikipedia:WikiProject_Football/Clubs\n \u2013 This is Wikipedia, not a football gazette.\n \u2013 Any unconfirmed and unsourced signing/transfer will be reverted at sight.\n \u2013 Thanks in advance.\n --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- -->\n[[File:David Villa NYCFC vs. Houston Dynamo- 5-30-2015 (18102079848).jpg|thumb|upright|Spanish World Cup-winning forward [[David Villa]] was the team's first captain.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|No.\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|Position\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|Player\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\"|Nation\n|-\n{{football squad player2 |no= 1 |nat=USA |pos=GK |name=[[Sean Johnson (soccer)|Sean Johnson]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no= 3 |nat=SWE |pos=DF |name=[[Anton Tinnerholm]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no= 4 |nat=LUX |pos=DF |name=[[Maxime Chanot]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no= 6 |nat=PER |pos=DF |name=[[Alexander Callens]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no= 8 |nat=FIN |pos=MF |name=[[Alexander Ring]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no= 9 |nat=BRA |pos=FW |name=[[H\u00e9ber Araujo dos Santos|H\u00e9ber]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=10 |nat=ARG |pos=MF |name=[[Maximiliano Moralez]] |other=[[Designated Player Rule|DP]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=11 |nat=ARG |pos=MF |name=[[Valent\u00edn Castellanos]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=13 |nat=USA |pos=GK |name=Luis Barraza}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=14 |nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Juan Pablo Torres (soccer)|Juan Pablo Torres]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=15 |nat=BLZ |pos=MF |name=[[Tony Rocha]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=16 |nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[James Sands]]|other=[[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|HG]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=17 |nat=SCO |pos=FW |name=[[Gary Mackay-Steven]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=19 |nat=PRY |pos=MF |name=[[Jes\u00fas Medina]] |other=[[Designated Player Rule|DP]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=20 |nat=ISL |pos=DF |name=[[Gu\u00f0mundur \u00de\u00f3rarinsson|Gudmundur Thorarinsson]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=22 |nat=CRC |pos=DF |name=[[R\u00f3nald Matarrita]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=23 |nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Gedion Zelalem]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=24 |nat=USA |pos=DF |name=Tayvon Gray|other=[[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|HG]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=25 |nat=USA |pos=DF |name=[[Joseph Scally|Joe Scally]]|other=[[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|HG]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=26 |nat=URU |pos=MF |name=[[Nicol\u00e1s Acevedo]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=28 |nat=ROM |pos=FW |name=[[Alexandru Mitri\u021b\u0103]]|other=[[Designated Player Rule|DP]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=29 |nat=LBY |pos=FW |name=[[Ismael Tajouri-Shradi]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=33 |nat=USA |pos=DF |name=[[Sebastien Ibeagha]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=41 |nat=USA |pos=GK |name=[[Brad Stuver]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=55 |nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Keaton Parks]]}}\n{{football squad player2 |no=80 |nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Justin Haak]]|other=[[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|HG]]}}\n{{football squad end2}}\n\n=== Current technical staff ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; color:#041E42; border:2px solid #FE5000;\" scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"|Executive\n{{Fb cs staff |bg=  |p=Chief executive officer |s= Brad Sims}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg=  |p=Vice president for partnerships |s= Ben Martin}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg=y |p=Vice president for communications |s= Sam Cooke}}\n{{Fb cs staff |bg=  |p=Sporting director |s= David Lee}}\n|-\n! style=\"background:#6CACE4; 