n-nycfc-president-will-take-clubs-board |title=Jon Patricof won't return as NYCFC president, will take club's board |date=October 4, 2018 |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|CEO\n!scope=row|{{flagicon|USA}} Brad Sims\n| align=left|January 1, 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/12/04/nycfc-hire-former-cleveland-cavaliers-exec-brad-sims-new-ceo |title=NYCFC hire former Cleveland Cavaliers exec Brad Sims as new CEO |last=Bogert |first=Tom |date=December 4, 2018 |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> \u2013 present\n|}\n\n== Affiliates and club academy ==\nThe [[United Soccer League|USL's]] [[Wilmington Hammerheads]] were New York City's first affiliate club, announced on January 16, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wilmingtonhammerheads.com/hammerheads-announce-mls-affiliation/ |title=HAMMERHEADS ANNOUNCE MLS AFFILIATION |publisher=Wilmington Hammerheads |access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> One year later, both clubs announced a long-term extension to that original agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://portcitydaily.com/2016/02/05/sports-wilmington-hammerheads-continue-mls-partnership-with-nycfc/ |title=Wilmington Hammerheads continue MLS partnership with NYCFC |work=Port City Daily |access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> On April 21, 2016, the club also announced that the [[Long Island Rough Riders]] would be their official [[Premier Development League]] partner beginning with the 2016 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2016/04/21/new-york-city-fc-announces-long-island-rough-riders-pdl-affiliate |title=New York City FC Announces Long Island Rough Riders as PDL Affiliate |date=April 21, 2016 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City Football Club |access-date=February 22, 2017}}</ref> After the Wilmington Hammerheads dropped to an amateur league following the 2016 season, New York City further announced another affiliation agreement, partnering with [[San Antonio FC|San Antonio]] on February 9, 2017. Sporting Director [[Claudio Reyna]] called the agreement \"an important affiliation for NYCFC with an ambitious, forward-thinking club like San Antonio, which shares our drive to grow the game within their own passionate soccer community.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/02/09/nycfc-announce-affiliation-san-antonio-fc |title=NYCFC Announce Affiliation with San Antonio FC |date=February 9, 2017 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City Football Club |access-date=February 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNew York City also began building its youth development program in April 2014 by partnering with eight local youth soccer clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2014/April/Affiliates |title=New York City FC to Provide Local Youth with World-Class Training and Resources, Appoints Paul Jeffries to Lead Club's Community Outreach Efforts |date=April 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728213130/http://nycfc.com/News/Latest-News/2014/April/Affiliates |archive-date=July 28, 2014 |access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> This foresaw the club formally announcing the creation of an academy in February 2015, beginning with a single team at U-13 and U-14 level.<ref name=\"academy\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/02/17/new-york-city-fc-launching-youth-academy-0 |title=New York City FC launching Youth Academy |date=February 17, 2015 |access-date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> The academy saw its first success in 2017, with the U-16 team winning the [[Generation Adidas Cup]], becoming the first major silverware earned by New York City in any capacity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/04/15/nycfc-u16s-are-generation-adidas-cup-champions |title=NYCFC U16s are Generation adidas Cup Champions! |last=Booth |first=Mark |date=April 16, 2017 |website=nycfc.com |publisher=New York City Football Club |access-date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Team records ==\n=== Year-by-year ===\n{{updated|October 23, 2019|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings |title=Standings}}</ref>}}\n\nList of the last three seasons completed by New York City. For the full season-by-season history and other data, see [[List of New York City FC records and statistics]].\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! colspan=7 class=\"unsortable\"|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]] regular season\n! colspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|Position\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|[[MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|[[Open Cup]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|[[CONCACAF Champions League|Champions<br />League]]\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=3 class=\"unsortable\"|Top scorer{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n|-\n!{{tooltip|P|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n!{{tooltip|Conf.|Conference position}}\n!{{tooltip|Overall|Overall position}}\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Player\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Goals\n|-\n| [[2017 New York City FC season|2017]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 9\n| 9\n| 56\n| 43\n| 57\n| 2nd\n| 2nd\n| Conference Semi-finals\n| [[2017 U.S. Open Cup|4R]]\n| DNQ\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[David Villa]]\n| 24\n|-\n| [[2018 New York City FC season|2018]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 10\n| 8\n| 59\n| 45\n| 56\n| 3rd\n| 7th\n| Conference Semi-finals\n| [[2018 U.S. Open Cup|4R]]\n| DNQ\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[David Villa]]\n| 14\n|-\n| [[2019 New York City FC season|2019]]\n| 34\n| 18\n| 6\n| 10\n| 63\n| 42\n| 64\n| 1st\n| 2nd\n| Conference Semi-finals\n| [[2019 U.S. Open Cup|QF]]\n| DNQ\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[H\u00e9ber Araujo dos Santos|H\u00e9ber]]\n| 15\n|}\n\n=== Head coaches ===\n* Includes regular season, playoff, CONCACAF Champions League, and Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup games.\n\n{{upd